from collections import deque

class MyStack:

    def __init__(self):
        self.q1 = deque()
        self.q2 = deque()

    def push(self, x: int) -> None:
        self.q2.append(x)
        while self.q1:
            self.q2.append(self.q1.popleft())
        self.q1, self.q2 = self.q2, self.q1

    def pop(self) -> int:
        return self.q1.popleft()

    def top(self) -> int:
        return self.q1[0]

    def empty(self) -> bool:
        return not self.q1
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n) for push, O(1) for pop, top, empty
space complexity: O(n)
energy implications: MEDIUM
explanation: This solution uses two queues to simulate a stack. The push operation moves all elements from the first queue to the second queue and then adds the new element to the second queue. This effectively reverses the order of the elements, making the last element added the first one to be removed. The pop, top, and empty operations are O(1) because they only involve removing or accessing the front element of the first queue. The space complexity is O(n) because in the worst case, all elements are moved from one queue to the other.

